</span></h1><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Mastering_effective_leadership_The_power_of_detachment_-_Dr_Richard_Dune.png?v=1704444416" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Mastering_effective_leadership_The_power_of_detachment_-_Dr_Richard_Dune.png?v=1704444416 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Mastering_effective_leadership_The_power_of_detachment_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_1000x.png?v=1704444416 768w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Mastering_effective_leadership_The_power_of_detachment_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_500x.png?v=1704444416 320w" width="1217" height="811" alt="Mastering effective leadership The power of detachment - Dr Richard Dune -.png__PID:bb52745a-67c7-4848-b3c5-35226401b6b4" title="Mastering effective leadership: The power of detachment - Dr Richard Dune -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-uojGG kTBJzQ pf-14_"/><p class="sc-fIosxK hdNOer pf-15_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-cLpAjG dTtSfA pf-17_">Image by drazenphoto via Envato Elements</span></p></div></div></div></div></div><div data-section-id="pf-d845" data-category="Generic Content" data-name="Matcha" data-pf-type="Section" class="sc-jlRLRk bizPpK pf-18_"><div style="--cw:1170px" class="sc-lkgTHX eDNqWj"><div class="sc-fFeiMQ etkQEf pf-19_ pf-r pf-c-cb pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:0px;--s-sm:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-FNXRL gpaAAN pf-20_"><p class="sc-fIosxK hdNOer pf-21_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-cLpAjG dTtSfA pf-23_">As leaders, we often find ourselves caught in the never-ending work cycle — constantly checking emails, strategising, and thinking about the next steps. But is this 'always-on' approach beneficial? Recent research from Harvard Business Review suggests otherwise.
<br><br>Let's dive into the intricacies of this issue and its personal challenges and discover the path to more effective leadership.
</span></p><h1 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-dFtzxp icSyEj pf-24_ _Y6RW61"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-cLpAjG dTtSfA pf-26_">The challenge  - The 'always-on' leader
</span></h1><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Unlocking_success_embracing_detachment_for_well-being_-_Dr_Richard_Dune.png?v=1704445092" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Unlocking_success_embracing_detachment_for_well-being_-_Dr_Richard_Dune.png?v=1704445092 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Unlocking_success_embracing_detachment_for_well-being_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_500x.png?v=1704445092 320w" width="1516" height="1010" alt="Unlocking success embracing detachment for well-being - Dr Richard Dune -.png__PID:96067341-1f5b-4169-9ac8-811552587062" title="Unlocking success: embracing detachment for well-being - Dr Richard Dune -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-uojGG kTBJzQ pf-27_"/><p class="sc-fIosxK hdNOer pf-28_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-cLpAjG dTtSfA pf-30_">Image by&nbsp;bernardbodo via Envato Elements</span></p><p class="sc-fIosxK hdNOer pf-31_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-cLpAjG dTtSfA pf-33_">Leadership comes with its set of challenges — high expectations, decision-making, and the continuous pursuit of excellence. Many leaders, including myself, have fallen into the trap of believing that constant engagement with work is synonymous with productivity and success.
<br><br>This lifestyle leads to working long hours, sacrificing weekends, and forgoing personal time.
</span></p><h1 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-dFtzxp icSyEj pf-34_ _Y6RW61"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-cLpAjG dTtSfA pf-36_">The revelation - Detachment is key
</span></h1><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/10_habits_of_highly_effective_leaders_Balancing_work_and_life_-_Dr_Richard_Dune.png?v=1704445317" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/10_habits_of_highly_effective_leaders_Balancing_work_and_life_-_Dr_Richard_Dune.png?v=1704445317 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/10_habits_of_highly_effective_leaders_Balancing_work_and_life_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_500x.png?v=1704445317 320w" width="1440" height="960" alt="10 habits of highly effective leaders Balancing work and life - Dr Richard Dune -.png__PID:c3f97b07-be1c-4933-8810-d8f09f9dad2e" title="10 habits of highly effective leaders: Balancing work and life - Dr Richard Dune -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-uojGG kTBJzQ pf-37_"/><p class="sc-fIosxK hdNOer pf-38_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-cLpAjG dTtSfA pf-40_">Image by CarlosBarquero via Envato Elements</span></p><p class="sc-fIosxK hdNOer pf-41_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-cLpAjG dTtSfA pf-43_">The article "Want to Be a Better Leader? Stop Thinking About Work After Hours" sheds light on a counterintuitive strategy — detachment. The study conducted over ten days involving leaders and their direct reports illustrates that mental detachment from work after hours leads to more recharged, effective, and positively perceived leaders.<br><br>Leaders who disconnect report feeling more energised, exhibit a stronger leadership identity and are viewed as more transformational by their teams.
<br>
</span></p><h1 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-dFtzxp icSyEj pf-44_ _Y6RW61"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-cLpAjG dTtSfA pf-46_">Understanding the pitfalls
</span></h1><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/The_key_to_sustainable_leadership_Embracing_detachment_-_Dr_Richard_Dune.png?v=1704445456" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/The_key_to_sustainable_leadership_Embracing_detachment_-_Dr_Richard_Dune.png?v=1704445456 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/The_key_to_sustainable_leadership_Embracing_detachment_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_500x.png?v=1704445456 320w" width="1500" height="1000" alt="The key to sustainable leadership Embracing detachment - Dr Richard Dune -.png__PID:072f70a5-dc06-4cb5-b626-caa905eb5ccd" title="The key to sustainable leadership: Embracing detachment - Dr Richard Dune -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-uojGG kTBJzQ pf-47_"/><p class="sc-fIosxK hdNOer pf-48_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-cLpAjG dTtSfA pf-50_">Image by Queenmoonlite via Envato Elements</span></p><ul style="--text-indent:0;--line-spacing:10px" data-pf-type="List2" class="sc-hjGZqJ dZgAAn pf-51_"><li tabindex="0" spellcheck="false" data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-gUQvok dVgjzi pf-52_"><b>Mental depletion </b>- Continuous work thoughts drain mental resources, leaving leaders feeling exhausted and less effective the next day.
</li><li tabindex="0" spellcheck="false" data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-gUQvok dVgjzi pf-54_"><b>Poor role identification</b> - Leaders who fail to disconnect struggle to embrace and perform in their leadership role fully.
</li><li tabindex="0" spellcheck="false" data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-gUQvok dVgjzi pf-56_"><b>Negative team perception</b> - Employees perceive leaders who don't detach as less transformational and powerful.
</li></ul><h1 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-dFtzxp icSyEj pf-58_ _Y6RW61"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-cLpAjG dTtSfA pf-60_">The power of recovery

</span></h1><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Recharge_and_thrive_the_importance_of_off-work_recovery_for_leaders_-_Dr_Richard_Dune.png?v=1704445576" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Recharge_and_thrive_the_importance_of_off-work_recovery_for_leaders_-_Dr_Richard_Dune.png?v=1704445576 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Recharge_and_thrive_the_importance_of_off-work_recovery_for_leaders_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_500x.png?v=1704445576 320w" width="1291" height="861" alt="Recharge and thrive the importance of off-work recovery for leaders - Dr Richard Dune -.png__PID:4fa35dc1-3b84-4849-ab69-56788eb737d6" title="Recharge and thrive: the importance of off-work recovery for leaders - Dr Richard Dune -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-uojGG kTBJzQ pf-61_"/><p class="sc-fIosxK hdNOer pf-62_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-cLpAjG dTtSfA pf-64_">Image by yavdat via Envato Elements</span></p><p class="sc-fIosxK hdNOer pf-65_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-cLpAjG dTtSfA pf-67_">The research highlights the importance of off-work recovery for leaders. Recovery isn't just about rest but mental disengagement and rejuvenation. This involves:
</span></p><ul style="--text-indent:0;--line-spacing:10px" data-pf-type="List2" class="sc-hjGZqJ dZgAAn pf-68_"><li tabindex="0" spellcheck="false" data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-gUQvok dVgjzi pf-69_"><b>Mastering new hobbies </b>- Engage in activities unrelated to work to refresh your mind.
</li><li tabindex="0" spellcheck="false" data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-gUQvok dVgjzi pf-71_"> Setting boundaries - Clearly define work hours and communicate these to your team.
</li><li tabindex="0" spellcheck="false" data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-gUQvok dVgjzi pf-73_"><b>Prioritising rest</b> - Ensure you have dedicated time for relaxation and personal interests.
</li></ul><h1 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-dFtzxp icSyEj pf-75_ _Y6RW61"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-cLpAjG dTtSfA pf-77_">Recommendations for leaders
</span></h1><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Finding_balance_How_to_achieve_sustainable_leadership_-_Dr_Richard_Dune.png?v=1704446043" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Finding_balance_How_to_achieve_sustainable_leadership_-_Dr_Richard_Dune.png?v=1704446043 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Finding_balance_How_to_achieve_sustainable_leadership_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_500x.png?v=1704446043 320w" width="1981" height="1321" alt="Finding balance How to achieve sustainable leadership - Dr Richard Dune -.png__PID:9450874f-b7e0-4361-93b5-60a8929e716c" title="Finding balance: How to achieve sustainable leadership - Dr Richard Dune -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-uojGG kTBJzQ pf-78_"/><p class="sc-fIosxK hdNOer pf-79_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-cLpAjG dTtSfA pf-81_">Image by amenic181 via Envato Elements</span></p><p class="sc-fIosxK hdNOer pf-82_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-cLpAjG dTtSfA pf-84_">To transform these insights into action, consider the following:
</span></p><ul style="--text-indent:0;--line-spacing:10px" data-pf-type="List2" class="sc-hjGZqJ dZgAAn pf-85_"><li tabindex="0" spellcheck="false" data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-gUQvok dVgjzi pf-86_"><b>Schedule 'Off-Work' time</b> - Treat your personal time with the same respect as your work appointments.
</li><li tabindex="0" spellcheck="false" data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-gUQvok dVgjzi pf-88_"><b>Communicate boundaries</b> - Set clear expectations regarding availability and emergency protocols with your team.
</li><li tabindex="0" spellcheck="false" data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-gUQvok dVgjzi pf-90_"><b>Diversify interests</b> - Encourage a life outside work by pursuing hobbies, spending time with loved ones, or engaging in community service.
</li><li tabindex="0" spellcheck="false" data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-gUQvok dVgjzi pf-92_"><b>Seek support </b>- Don't hesitate to reach out to mentors, coaches, or peers to share experiences and strategies for effective detachment.
</li></ul><h1 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-dFtzxp icSyEj pf-94_ _Y6RW61"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-cLpAjG dTtSfA pf-96_">The journey forward
</span></h1><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Mental_disengagement_for_leaders_Unlocking_productivity_and_well-being_-_Dr_Richard_Dune.png?v=1704446157" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Mental_disengagement_for_leaders_Unlocking_productivity_and_well-being_-_Dr_Richard_Dune.png?v=1704446157 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Mental_disengagement_for_leaders_Unlocking_productivity_and_well-being_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_500x.png?v=1704446157 320w" width="1805" height="1205" alt="Mental disengagement for leaders Unlocking productivity and well-being - Dr Richard Dune -.png__PID:788ac4b9-da11-466a-89bc-72c69de82fb5" title="Mental disengagement for leaders: Unlocking productivity and well-being - Dr Richard Dune -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-uojGG kTBJzQ pf-97_"/><p class="sc-fIosxK hdNOer pf-98_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-cLpAjG dTtSfA pf-100_">Image by ckstockphoto via Envato Elements</span></p><p class="sc-fIosxK hdNOer pf-101_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-cLpAjG dTtSfA pf-103_">As we move forward, it's essential to recognise that detaching from work isn't a sign of weakness but a strategic approach to sustainable leadership. Here's how you can start this journey:
</span></p><ul style="--text-indent:0;--line-spacing:10px" data-pf-type="List2" class="sc-hjGZqJ dZgAAn pf-104_"><li tabindex="0" spellcheck="false" data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-gUQvok dVgjzi pf-105_"> <b>Reflect on your habits</b> - Identify your current work-life patterns and acknowledge the need for change.
</li><li tabindex="0" spellcheck="false" data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-gUQvok dVgjzi pf-107_"><b>Set incremental goals</b> - Begin with small changes in your routine and gradually increase your detachment time.
</li><li tabindex="0" spellcheck="false" data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-gUQvok dVgjzi pf-109_"><b>Celebrate progress</b> - Recognise and celebrate the positive impact of detachment on your well-being and leadership.
</li></ul><h1 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-dFtzxp icSyEj pf-111_ _Y6RW61"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-cLpAjG dTtSfA pf-113_">Conclusion
</span></h1><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Drawing_boundaries_A_guide_to_effective_leadership_habits_-_Conclusion_-_Dr_Richard_Dune.png?v=1704446300" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Drawing_boundaries_A_guide_to_effective_leadership_habits_-_Conclusion_-_Dr_Richard_Dune.png?v=1704446300 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Drawing_boundaries_A_guide_to_effective_leadership_habits_-_Conclusion_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_500x.png?v=1704446300 320w" width="1200" height="800" alt="Drawing boundaries A guide to effective leadership habits - Conclusion - Dr Richard Dune -.png__PID:e09334b2-e657-4093-a2ff-118ce0a7ff96" title="Drawing boundaries: A guide to effective leadership habits - Conclusion - Dr Richard Dune -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-uojGG kTBJzQ pf-114_"/><p class="sc-fIosxK hdNOer pf-115_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-cLpAjG dTtSfA pf-117_">Image by IrynaKhabliuk via Envato Elements</span></p><p class="sc-fIosxK hdNOer pf-118_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-cLpAjG dTtSfA pf-120_">The idea of disconnecting from work in a hyper-connected world may seem daunting, but the benefits are clear. As leaders, it's our responsibility to model healthy work habits for our well-being and the benefit of our teams and organisations.
